{"kind": "codeblock", "id": "c48ab4690369a818", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#run-on-a-fixed-interval", "position": 0, "language": "text", "text": "/loop 5m check if the deployment finished and tell me what happened", "preceding_paragraph": "When you supply an interval, Claude converts it to a cron expression, schedules the job, and confirms the cadence and job ID.", "in_codegroup": false, "codegroup_id": null}
{"kind": "section", "id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#run-on-a-fixed-interval", "page_url": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md", "anchor": "run-on-a-fixed-interval", "breadcrumb": "Run prompts on a schedule > Run a prompt repeatedly with /loop > Run on a fixed interval", "level": 3, "position": 3, "text": "When you supply an interval, Claude converts it to a cron expression, schedules the job, and confirms the cadence and job ID.\n\nThe interval can lead the prompt as a bare token like `30m`, or trail it as a clause like `every 2 hours`. Supported units are `s` for seconds, `m` for minutes, `h` for hours, and `d` for days.\n\nSeconds are rounded up to the nearest minute since cron has one-minute granularity. Intervals that don't map to a clean cron step, such as `7m` or `90m`, are rounded to the nearest interval that does and Claude tells you what it picked.", "synthesized": false, "parent_section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#run-a-prompt-repeatedly-with-loop", "external_links": []}
{"kind": "codeblock", "id": "f29fc21a24f4fa90", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#let-claude-choose-the-interval", "position": 0, "language": "text", "text": "/loop check whether CI passed and address any review comments", "preceding_paragraph": "The example below checks CI and review comments, with Claude waiting longer between iterations once the PR goes quiet:", "in_codegroup": false, "codegroup_id": null}
{"kind": "callout", "id": "7117ad0523ca5730", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#let-claude-choose-the-interval", "position": 0, "callout_kind": "note", "text": "On Bedrock, Vertex AI, and Microsoft Foundry, a prompt with no interval runs on a fixed 10-minute schedule instead."}
{"kind": "section", "id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#let-claude-choose-the-interval", "page_url": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md", "anchor": "let-claude-choose-the-interval", "breadcrumb": "Run prompts on a schedule > Run a prompt repeatedly with /loop > Let Claude choose the interval", "level": 3, "position": 4, "text": "When you omit the interval, Claude chooses one dynamically instead of running on a fixed cron schedule. After each iteration it picks a delay between one minute and one hour based on what it observed: short waits while a build is finishing or a PR is active, longer waits when nothing is pending. The chosen delay and the reason for it are printed at the end of each iteration.\n\nThe example below checks CI and review comments, with Claude waiting longer between iterations once the PR goes quiet:\n\nWhen you ask for a dynamic `/loop` schedule, Claude may use the Monitor tool directly. Monitor runs a background script and streams each output line back, which avoids polling altogether and is often more token-efficient and responsive than re-running a prompt on an interval.\n\nA dynamically scheduled loop appears in your scheduled task list like any other task, so you can list or cancel it the same way. The jitter rules don't apply to it, but the seven-day expiry does: the loop ends automatically seven days after you start it.", "synthesized": false, "parent_section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#run-a-prompt-repeatedly-with-loop", "external_links": []}
{"kind": "codeblock", "id": "fef1ab5a8b630d2d", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#run-the-built-in-maintenance-prompt", "position": 0, "language": "text", "text": "/loop", "preceding_paragraph": "Claude does not start new initiatives outside that scope, and irreversible actions such as pushing or deleting only proceed when they continue something the transcript already authorized.", "in_codegroup": false, "codegroup_id": null}
{"kind": "callout", "id": "b5fbaaba3cb2c8c4", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#run-the-built-in-maintenance-prompt", "position": 0, "callout_kind": "note", "text": "On Bedrock, Vertex AI, and Microsoft Foundry, `/loop` with no prompt prints the usage message instead of starting the maintenance loop."}
{"kind": "section", "id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#run-the-built-in-maintenance-prompt", "page_url": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md", "anchor": "run-the-built-in-maintenance-prompt", "breadcrumb": "Run prompts on a schedule > Run a prompt repeatedly with /loop > Run the built-in maintenance prompt", "level": 3, "position": 5, "text": "When you omit the prompt, Claude uses a built-in maintenance prompt instead of one you supply. On each iteration it works through the following, in order:\n\n- continue any unfinished work from the conversation\n- tend to the current branch's pull request: review comments, failed CI runs, merge conflicts\n- run cleanup passes such as bug hunts or simplification when nothing else is pending\n\nClaude does not start new initiatives outside that scope, and irreversible actions such as pushing or deleting only proceed when they continue something the transcript already authorized.\n\nA bare `/loop` runs this prompt at a dynamically chosen interval. Add an interval, for example `/loop 15m`, to run it on a fixed schedule instead. To replace the built-in prompt with your own default, see Customize the default prompt with loop.md.", "synthesized": false, "parent_section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#run-a-prompt-repeatedly-with-loop", "external_links": []}
{"kind": "tablerow", "id": "414b7be80f8ffc19", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#customize-the-default-prompt-with-loopmd", "position": 0, "table_position": 0, "headers": ["path", "scope"], "cells": ["`.claude/loop.md`", "Project-level. Takes precedence when both files exist."]}
{"kind": "tablerow", "id": "bf3a127b34f81659", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#customize-the-default-prompt-with-loopmd", "position": 1, "table_position": 0, "headers": ["path", "scope"], "cells": ["`~/.claude/loop.md`", "User-level. Applies in any project that does not define its own."]}
{"kind": "codeblock", "id": "e905621071719f73", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#customize-the-default-prompt-with-loopmd", "position": 0, "language": "markdown", "text": "Check the `release/next` PR. If CI is red, pull the failing job log,\ndiagnose, and push a minimal fix. If new review comments have arrived,\naddress each one and resolve the thread. If everything is green and\nquiet, say so in one line.", "preceding_paragraph": "The file is plain Markdown with no required structure. Write it as if you were typing the `/loop` prompt directly. The following example keeps a release branch healthy:", "in_codegroup": false, "codegroup_id": null}
{"kind": "section", "id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#customize-the-default-prompt-with-loopmd", "page_url": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md", "anchor": "customize-the-default-prompt-with-loopmd", "breadcrumb": "Run prompts on a schedule > Run a prompt repeatedly with /loop > Customize the default prompt with loop.md", "level": 3, "position": 6, "text": "A `loop.md` file replaces the built-in maintenance prompt with your own instructions. It defines a single default prompt for bare `/loop`, not a list of separate scheduled tasks, and is ignored whenever you supply a prompt on the command line. To schedule additional prompts alongside it, use `/loop <prompt>` or ask Claude directly.\n\nClaude looks for the file in two locations and uses the first one it finds.\n\nThe file is plain Markdown with no required structure. Write it as if you were typing the `/loop` prompt directly. The following example keeps a release branch healthy:\n\nEdits to `loop.md` take effect on the next iteration, so you can refine the instructions while a loop is running. When no `loop.md` exists in either location, the loop falls back to the built-in maintenance prompt. Keep the file concise: content beyond 25,000 bytes is truncated.", "synthesized": false, "parent_section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#run-a-prompt-repeatedly-with-loop", "external_links": []}
{"kind": "section", "id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#stop-a-loop", "page_url": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md", "anchor": "stop-a-loop", "breadcrumb": "Run prompts on a schedule > Run a prompt repeatedly with /loop > Stop a loop", "level": 3, "position": 7, "text": "To stop a `/loop` while it is waiting for the next iteration, press `Esc`. This clears the pending wakeup so the loop does not fire again. Tasks you scheduled by asking Claude directly are not affected by `Esc` and stay in place until you delete them.", "synthesized": false, "parent_section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#run-a-prompt-repeatedly-with-loop", "external_links": []}
{"kind": "section", "id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#run-a-prompt-repeatedly-with-loop", "page_url": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md", "anchor": "run-a-prompt-repeatedly-with-loop", "breadcrumb": "Run prompts on a schedule > Run a prompt repeatedly with /loop", "level": 2, "position": 2, "text": "The `/loop` bundled skill is the quickest way to run a prompt on repeat while the session stays open. Both the interval and the prompt are optional, and what you provide determines how the loop behaves.\n\nYou can also pass another command as the prompt, for example `/loop 20m /review-pr 1234`, to re-run a packaged workflow each iteration.", "synthesized": false, "parent_section_id": null, "external_links": []}
{"kind": "codeblock", "id": "7887cc9fbec51760", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#set-a-one-time-reminder", "position": 0, "language": "text", "text": "remind me at 3pm to push the release branch", "preceding_paragraph": "For one-shot reminders, describe what you want in natural language instead of using `/loop`. Claude schedules a single-fire task that deletes itself after running.", "in_codegroup": false, "codegroup_id": null}
{"kind": "codeblock", "id": "dfdff452c0bb03be", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#set-a-one-time-reminder", "position": 1, "language": "text", "text": "in 45 minutes, check whether the integration tests passed", "preceding_paragraph": "For one-shot reminders, describe what you want in natural language instead of using `/loop`. Claude schedules a single-fire task that deletes itself after running.", "in_codegroup": false, "codegroup_id": null}
{"kind": "section", "id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#set-a-one-time-reminder", "page_url": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md", "anchor": "set-a-one-time-reminder", "breadcrumb": "Run prompts on a schedule > Set a one-time reminder", "level": 2, "position": 8, "text": "For one-shot reminders, describe what you want in natural language instead of using `/loop`. Claude schedules a single-fire task that deletes itself after running.\n\nClaude pins the fire time to a specific minute and hour using a cron expression and confirms when it will fire.", "synthesized": false, "parent_section_id": null, "external_links": []}
{"kind": "codeblock", "id": "fb56d2c51c709995", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#manage-scheduled-tasks", "position": 0, "language": "text", "text": "what scheduled tasks do I have?", "preceding_paragraph": "Ask Claude in natural language to list or cancel tasks, or reference the underlying tools directly.", "in_codegroup": false, "codegroup_id": null}
