{"kind": "tablerow", "id": "e335a3de0814e31b", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#manage-scheduled-tasks", "position": 2, "table_position": 0, "headers": ["tool", "purpose"], "cells": ["`CronDelete`", "Cancel a task by ID."]}
{"kind": "section", "id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#manage-scheduled-tasks", "page_url": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md", "anchor": "manage-scheduled-tasks", "breadcrumb": "Run prompts on a schedule > Manage scheduled tasks", "level": 2, "position": 9, "text": "Ask Claude in natural language to list or cancel tasks, or reference the underlying tools directly.\n\nUnder the hood, Claude uses these tools:\n\nEach scheduled task has an 8-character ID you can pass to `CronDelete`. A session can hold up to 50 scheduled tasks at once.", "synthesized": false, "parent_section_id": null, "external_links": []}
{"kind": "section", "id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#jitter", "page_url": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md", "anchor": "jitter", "breadcrumb": "Run prompts on a schedule > How scheduled tasks run > Jitter", "level": 3, "position": 11, "text": "To avoid every session hitting the API at the same wall-clock moment, the scheduler adds a small deterministic offset to fire times:\n\n- Recurring tasks fire up to 10% of their period late, capped at 15 minutes. An hourly job might fire anywhere from `:00` to `:06`.\n- One-shot tasks scheduled for the top or bottom of the hour fire up to 90 seconds early.\n\nThe offset is derived from the task ID, so the same task always gets the same offset. If exact timing matters, pick a minute that is not `:00` or `:30`, for example `3 9 * * *` instead of `0 9 * * *`, and the one-shot jitter will not apply.", "synthesized": false, "parent_section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#how-scheduled-tasks-run", "external_links": []}
{"kind": "section", "id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#seven-day-expiry", "page_url": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md", "anchor": "seven-day-expiry", "breadcrumb": "Run prompts on a schedule > How scheduled tasks run > Seven-day expiry", "level": 3, "position": 12, "text": "Recurring tasks automatically expire 7 days after creation. The task fires one final time, then deletes itself. This bounds how long a forgotten loop can run. If you need a recurring task to last longer, cancel and recreate it before it expires, or use Routines or Desktop scheduled tasks for durable scheduling.", "synthesized": false, "parent_section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#how-scheduled-tasks-run", "external_links": []}
{"kind": "section", "id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#how-scheduled-tasks-run", "page_url": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md", "anchor": "how-scheduled-tasks-run", "breadcrumb": "Run prompts on a schedule > How scheduled tasks run", "level": 2, "position": 10, "text": "The scheduler checks every second for due tasks and enqueues them at low priority. A scheduled prompt fires between your turns, not while Claude is mid-response. If Claude is busy when a task comes due, the prompt waits until the current turn ends.\n\nAll times are interpreted in your local timezone. A cron expression like `0 9 * * *` means 9am wherever you're running Claude Code, not UTC.", "synthesized": false, "parent_section_id": null, "external_links": []}
{"kind": "tablerow", "id": "c191dfb13aad7a4a", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#cron-expression-reference", "position": 0, "table_position": 0, "headers": ["example", "meaning"], "cells": ["`*/5 * * * *`", "Every 5 minutes"]}
{"kind": "tablerow", "id": "b06c5df63ec26b78", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#cron-expression-reference", "position": 1, "table_position": 0, "headers": ["example", "meaning"], "cells": ["`0 * * * *`", "Every hour on the hour"]}
{"kind": "tablerow", "id": "168b703ef140fbb5", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#cron-expression-reference", "position": 2, "table_position": 0, "headers": ["example", "meaning"], "cells": ["`7 * * * *`", "Every hour at 7 minutes past"]}
{"kind": "tablerow", "id": "17d5a78e0119a6e3", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#cron-expression-reference", "position": 3, "table_position": 0, "headers": ["example", "meaning"], "cells": ["`0 9 * * *`", "Every day at 9am local"]}
{"kind": "tablerow", "id": "0a36205643e8db8c", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#cron-expression-reference", "position": 4, "table_position": 0, "headers": ["example", "meaning"], "cells": ["`0 9 * * 1-5`", "Weekdays at 9am local"]}
{"kind": "tablerow", "id": "7737306a21622c5e", "section_id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#cron-expression-reference", "position": 5, "table_position": 0, "headers": ["example", "meaning"], "cells": ["`30 14 15 3 *`", "March 15 at 2:30pm local"]}
{"kind": "section", "id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#cron-expression-reference", "page_url": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md", "anchor": "cron-expression-reference", "breadcrumb": "Run prompts on a schedule > Cron expression reference", "level": 2, "position": 13, "text": "`CronCreate` accepts standard 5-field cron expressions: `minute hour day-of-month month day-of-week`. All fields support wildcards (`*`), single values (`5`), steps (`*/15`), ranges (`1-5`), and comma-separated lists (`1,15,30`).\n\nDay-of-week uses `0` or `7` for Sunday through `6` for Saturday. Extended syntax like `L`, `W`, `?`, and name aliases such as `MON` or `JAN` is not supported.\n\nWhen both day-of-month and day-of-week are constrained, a date matches if either field matches. This follows standard vixie-cron semantics.", "synthesized": false, "parent_section_id": null, "external_links": []}
{"kind": "section", "id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#disable-scheduled-tasks", "page_url": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md", "anchor": "disable-scheduled-tasks", "breadcrumb": "Run prompts on a schedule > Disable scheduled tasks", "level": 2, "position": 14, "text": "Set `CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_CRON=1` in your environment to disable the scheduler entirely. The cron tools and `/loop` become unavailable, and any already-scheduled tasks stop firing. See Environment variables for the full list of disable flags.", "synthesized": false, "parent_section_id": null, "external_links": []}
{"kind": "section", "id": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md#limitations", "page_url": "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks.md", "anchor": "limitations", "breadcrumb": "Run prompts on a schedule > Limitations", "level": 2, "position": 15, "text": "Session-scoped scheduling has inherent constraints:\n\n- Tasks only fire while Claude Code is running and idle. Closing the terminal or letting the session exit stops them firing.\n- No catch-up for missed fires. If a task's scheduled time passes while Claude is busy on a long-running request, it fires once when Claude becomes idle, not once per missed interval.\n- Starting a fresh conversation clears all session-scoped tasks. Resuming with `claude --resume` or `claude --continue` restores tasks that have not expired: recurring tasks within seven days of creation, and one-shot tasks whose scheduled time has not yet passed. Background Bash and monitor tasks are never restored on resume.\n\nFor cron-driven automation that needs to run unattended:\n\n- Routines: run on Anthropic-managed infrastructure on a schedule, via API call, or on GitHub events\n- GitHub Actions: use a `schedule` trigger in CI\n- Desktop scheduled tasks: run locally on your machine", "synthesized": false, "parent_section_id": null, "external_links": []}
